Electrolyte effects on ECG

Hyperkalemia
EKG changes progress from peaked T-waves to widened QRS and eventually to ventricular tachycardia, fibrillation or pulseless electrical activity arrest.  These progressive changes can correlate with rising potassium levels. For example, peaked T waves might correspond with a potassium level of approximately 6 mmol/L, whereas cardiac arrest generally occurs at higher levels.

Hypokalemia
EKG changes can include increased amplitude and width of P wave, T wave flattening and inversion, prominent U waves and apparent long QT intervals due to merging of the T and U wave.
The U-wave is a deflection following the T wave. Hypokalemia causes enlarged and prominent T waves on the EKG. Potassium levels that are critically low (<1.7 mmol/L) can lead to torsades de pointes or“twisting of the points”, a polymorphic ventricular tachycardia.

Hypercalcaemia
The most common EKG finding associated with hypercalcemia is shortening of the QT interval. In severe cases, Osborn or J waves might be seen or ventricular fibrillation might ensue. Recognition of these EKG findings can prompt urgent treatment.

Hypocalcemia
The most common finding on EKG in patients with hypocalcemia is a prolonged QT interval.

Cardiac glycosides reversibly inhibit the sodium-potassium-ATPase, causing an increase in intracellular sodium and a decrease in intracellular potassium.

Overall effects : increased contractile velocity (increased contractility) and decreased heart rate.
1️⃣ Heart failure - inhibition of Na/K ATPase -> increased intra-myocyte sodium -> decreased Na calcium exchange -> reduced secretion of calcium -> increased intracellular calcium -> contractility increased.
However, elevated intracellular calcium also increases risk of arrhythmias.

2️⃣ In patients with HF, digoxin also inhibits sympathetic outflow and augments parasympathetic tone.
Increased parasympathetic tone to the SA node and AV node ->
(via hypersensitization of carotid sinus baroreceptors, central stimulation, increased vagal output, and possible potentiation of the effect of acetylcholine on the sinoatrial [SA] node) -> slowing the firing of the SA node and prolonging conduction at the atrioventricular (AV) node. -> supratherapeutic doses can cause sinus brady, AV block, arrhythmias
Is a water soluble drug (renally excreted) ?but has large volume of distribution - Distributed within skeletal and cardiac muscle. Patients with low muscle mass (elderly) or renal failure will need loading dose adjustment.
Drug has a large Vd. so it's makes sense that it exerts it's effects on muscle.
Especially hypokalemia or hypomagnesemia can potentiate toxicity.
Hypercalcemia can increase risk of toxicity. Hypocalcemia and nullify digoxin effects. -> maintain normal electrolyte levels.
Renal dysfunction increases digoxin levels and often precipitate toxicity!
Acute toxicity is uncommon - Hyperkalemia (inhibition of Na/K ATPase), hypomagnesemia, hypoxia will predispose to exagerrated action of digoxin. - Correct before administration.

Regulation of Respiration

#2022BSQ

[!TIP] Overview
There are chemical and non chemical stimuli for regulation of respiratoion.
Chemical stimuli provide the baseline inputs for regulation which are then modified by the non chemical stimuli.
Respiratory regulation is done to maintain PCO2, PO2 and pH.
The sensors in the system are central and peripheral chemoreceptors. They are sensitive to different parameters.
Input is integrated in the medulla.
Effectors are the respiratory muscles.
Since wider inspired PO2s can be tolerated by the body, the main regulators of respiratory drive in most states are PCO2 and pH.
PO2 can trigger respiration if PO2 drops very low.

Anaemia doest not affect PaO2 in normal respiratory physiology

Therefore, the receptors are not stimulated in conditions such as anemia or carbon monoxide poisoning, in which the amount of dissolved O2 in the blood reaching the receptors is generally normal, even though the combined O2 in the blood is markedly decreased. - Ganong

Chemical regulation of respiration


Respiration is regulated so that arterial CO2, O2 and pH are maintained within certain limits.
The sensors for this system are

  1. Central chemoreceptors in the aortic bodies and carotid bodies.
    1. They send afferents via the glossopharyngeal nerve
  2. Peripheral chemoreceptors
    1. They send afferents via the vagal nerve.

These afferent signals stimulate the respiratory centers (PreBOTC) in the medulla to increase the rate and depth of respiration.

Central chemoreceptors Peripheral chemoreceptors
Ventral surface of medulla Aortic and carotid bodies
Sense pH (via PCO2) diffusion Sense low PO2 and high PCO2 and probaly low pH
do NOT sense O2 Only sensor for O2 level
Can be desensitized Cannot be desensitized

Source- desensitization
Illustration of the above: Denervation of peripheral chemoreceptor will abolish PO2 response and reduce pH response. PCO2 response will be only slightly reduced.

Many graphs illustrate the influece of PO2, pCO2 and pH on respiratory rate:




Overall, PCO2 exerts the most influence on respiratory control.
why?
PaO2 sensitive glomus cells in the peripheral chemoreceptors increase firing as soon as the PO2 drops below 100.
However this doesn't translate into increased respiratory rate because:

  1. Desaturated Hb is less acidic -> increases blood pH -> decreases pH based respiratory drive.
  2. increased ventilation due to hypoxia -> CO2 washout -> decreased pCO2 and increased pH -> inhibition of respiratory drive.

PO2 based resiratory drive overrides the above two factors when PO2 drops to 'dangerously' low levels (i.e PaO2 approx 60.)
Lower PO2 levels will directly inhibit the respiratory center.

Not affected by BCG vaccination.
